ARRAYS in JS --
let fruits = ["apple" , "orange" , "coconut"];
fruits.push("walnut"); -- pushes new element to back of the array
fruits.pop( ); -- removes last element
fruits.unshift("mango"); -- adds element to the top the arrray.
fruits.shift( ); -- removes element from the top of the array.

fruits.length -- gives length of the array.
fruits.indexOf("apple") -- gives 0 as index of apple in array. If element doesnt exist then it returns -1.

for(let i=0 ; i<fruits.length ; i++)
{
	console.log(fruits[i]);
}
for(let fruit of fruits) -- advanced for loop.
{
	console.log(fruit);
}
fruits.sort( ) -- sorts the array. -- ascending
friuits.sort( ).reverse( ) -- sorts the array in reverse order. -- descending.

SPREAD Operator -- ( ... )
allows an iterable such as an array or string to be expanded into seperate elements.

let numbers = [ 1 , 2 , 3 , 4 , 5 ];
let max = Math.max(numbers) -- wrong as it cannot iterate to find the max no.
so we use the spread operator -- max = Math.max( ...numbers );

for strings too it can be used -- let name = "Ronit";
let letters = [...name]; -- unpacks the string into seperate elements.
console.log(letters);

We can join them again by using the join method --
letters = [...name].join("-");

let fruits = ["apples","oranges","guavas"];
let newfruits = [...fruits]; -- Shallow copy of array fruits.
We can also join diffn arrays while copying like  -- 
let newfruits = [...fruits, ...vegetables , "eggs" , "milk"];

REST parameters --
rest parameters = (...rest) allow a function work with a variable number of arguments by bundling them into an array.
-- Bundles seperate elements into an array

const food1 ="Pizza";
const food2 ="Burger";
const food3 = "Sushi";
const food4 ="Ramen";

function  openFridge(...foods){ // accepts a number of arguments and combine them into an array -- foods
	console.log(foods);
}

openFridge(food1,foods,food3,food4);

We use rest parameters to combine parameters and Spread operator to seperate individual elements from the array.
Rest parameters also help in combining strings into one single string.

function fullname(...strings){
	return strings.join(" ");
}
console.log(fullname("Mr.", "Ronit" , "Dey"));

-- em for font size relative to the parent.
-- rem for font size relative to the root.

Dice Roller code -- JS 
const values = [ ];
const images = [ ];
for (let i=0 ; i<numOfDice ; i++){
	const value = Math.floor(Math.random()*6)+1;
	values.push(value);
	images.push(`<img src="dice_images/${value}.png" alt="Dice : ${value}">`); -- Adds the image component to the Array.	
}

dicResult.textContent = `Dice: ${values.join(",")}`;
dicImages.innerHTML = images.join(` `);

CALLBACKS -- 
a function that is passed as a argument to another function.

Used to handle asynchronous operations:
Reading a file
Network requests
Interacting with database.

"Hey when ur done then call this next"

To use a callback -- we use a function that is passed as an argument to another function.
hello(goodbye); -- Dont add () after the function inside the arguments or we will call the function instantly.

sum(displayConsole, 12, 15);

function sum(callback , x , y){
    let result = x+y;
    callback(result);
}

function displayConsole(result){
    console.log(result);
}

ARRAYS -- .forEach( )--
method used to iterate over the elements of an array and apply a specified function (callback) to each element 

array.forEach(callback) -- element index and array are provided.
let numbers = [1,2,3,4,5,6];
function display(element){
    console.log(element);
}

numbers.forEach(display);

-- .map( ) --
accepts a callback and applies that function to each element of an array then return a new array.

-- .filter( ) -- creates a new array by filtering out elements
let numbers = [1,2,3,4,5,6];
let evenNums = numbers.filter(isEven);

function isEven(element){
    return element % 2 === 0;
}
console.log(evenNums); --- returns [2,4,6]

.reduce( ) -- reduces the elements of an array into a single value.

** Can find max element by using Math.max( ) -- just like in Java

Functions --
func declarations -- define a reusable block of code that performs a specific task.
func expressions -- a way to define functions as values or variables.

const hello = function( ){    // Passing function as variable
	console.log("hello!");
}

hello( ); -- normal calling
setTimeout(hello , 3000)    -- function passed as argument.
 -- function is executed after 3 seconds.(measured in milli-seconds)

 We can pass entire functions as argument too in JS -- 
 setTimeout(function( ){    // setTimeout(callback , time) --- accepts a callback from a function and a time to delay the execution of the function.
 	console.log("Hello");
 } , 3000);

const numbers = [1,2,3,4,5,6];
const squares = numbers.map(function(element){
	return Math.pow(element,2);
});
console.log(squares);

Arrow Functions --

Functions used in --
Callbacks in asynchronous operations 
High-order functions 
Closures
Event Listeners

Arrow Functions -- Concise way to write function expressions good for simple functions that you use only once 
(parameter) => some code.

const hello = (name) => {console.log(`Hello! ${name}`)};    // arrow one liner function.
hello("Ronit");

OBJECTS in Javascript --
A collection of related properties and/or methods. Can represent real world objects (people, products, places)
objects = { key : value, function( )}

const person = {
	firstname : "Ronit",
	lastname : "Dey",
	age : 30,
}

console.log(person.age); -- gives value 30.

this -- reference to the object where THIS is used (the object depends on the immediate context)
person.name = this.name;

const person = {
	name : "Ronit",
	favfood : "Pizza",
	sayHello : function( ){console.log(`Say Hi to ${this.name}`)}
}

** this keyword doesnt work with Arrow functions and this. in that case still refers to the window and not the current object.

CONSTRUCTORS in JS --
Special method for defining the properties and methods of objects.

function Car(make, model, year, colour){
	this.make = make;
	this.model = model;
	this.year = year;
	this.colour =colour;
}

const Car1 = new Car("Honda", "Civic", "2016", "Red");

CLASS in JS --
Provides a more structured and cleaner way to work with objects compared to
traditional constructor functions ex. static keyword, encapsulation, inheritance etc.

class Product {
	constructor(name, price){
		this.name = name;
		this.price = price;
	}
	displayProduct( ){
		console.log(`Procudt: ${this.name}`);
	}
}

Static keyword -- 
defines properties or methods that belong to a class itself rather than the objects created from that class 
(class owns anything static, not the objects)  -- We dont need to create any object to use the property.

 class Mathutil{
 	static PI = 3.14159;

 	static getDiameter(radius){
 		return radius *2;
 	}
 }
 To access static variable or function -- Classname.variable name -- Mathutil.PI , Mathutil.getDiameter( ).

Inheritance in JS --
allows a new class to inherit properties and methods from an existing class and helps with code reusability.

We use the `extends` keyword to inherit from classes.
class Animal {
	alive = true;
	sleep(){
		console.log(`This ${this.name} is sleeping`);
	}
}
class Rabbit extends Animal{
	name = "Rabbit";
}

const rabbit = new Rabbit();

// rabbit.alive = false;
console.log(rabbit.alive);
rabbit.sleep();


SUPER  keyword in JS --
Used in classes to call the constructor or access the properties and methods of a parent (Superclass)
this -- used to specify the current object.
super -- used to specify the parent object.

For child classes extending from the parent class. We first have to run the constructor of the parrent class --
using the super( ) method and then we can sun the constructors of the child class.


Getters and Setters -- 
Getter -- a special method that makes a property readable.
Setter -- a special method that makes a property writable.

Used to validate and modify a value when reading / writing a property.


